<paper id="1602747136"><title>On the Security of the Permuted Kernel Identification Scheme</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="PAA/TSA/SRC" id="2191030170">Thierry Baritaud</author><author org="PAA/TSA/SRC" id="2763575731">Mireille Campana</author><author org="PAA/TSA/SRC" id="2211994766">Pascal Chauvaud</author><author org="PAA/TSA/SRC" id="2124974951">Henri Gilbert</author></authors><n_citation>12</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>90698540</reference><reference>2079116027</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48071-4_21</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.51232">Kernel (linear algebra)</keyword><keyword weight="0.43726">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.59173">Identification scheme</keyword><keyword weight="0.46038">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.46743">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.48296">Smart card</keyword><keyword weight="0.46975">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.49904">Computation</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A zero-knowledge identification scheme built upon the so-called Permuted Kernel Problem (PKP) was proposed by Adi Shamir in 1989 [1].In this paper, we present a time-memory trade-off leading to a reduction of the computation time for solving the PKP problem, as compared with the best known attack mentioned in [1].</abstract></paper>